ðŸ”„ STP (Spanning Tree Protocol)

ðŸ‘‰ Soch le ek city road network hai:

            Agar har road har jagah jodti rahe to traffic jam (loop) ho jayega.
            
            Isliye traffic police kuch roads ko bandh (block) kar dete hain, aur ek main road (root bridge) choose karte hain.
            
            Agar main road toot jaye, to backup road khul jati hai.

    STP bhi yehi karta hai:

        Works in Switching (Layer 2).
        
        Stops loops in LAN with many switches.
        
        Selects a root bridge as main path.
        
        Blocks extra links (like traffic police).
        
        Opens backup link if main fails.
        
        Prevents broadcast storm (network traffic jam).
        
        IEEE 802.1D standard.
        
        Increases reliability.
        
        Used inside organizationsâ€™ LAN.
        
        Example â†’ Multiple office switches connected in a ring.


ðŸ“© UDP (User Datagram Protocol)

ðŸ‘‰ Soch le tu apne dost ko postcard bhej raha hai:

            Tu seedha daal diya postbox me, bina phone karke confirm kiya ki wo ghar par hai ya nahi.
            
            Shayad postcard pohoch jaaye, shayad kho bhi jaye.
            
            Lekin postcard jaldi pahuchta hai, bina extra formalities ke.


UDP bhi yehi karta hai:

        Works in Transport Layer (Layer 4).
        
        Connectionless â†’ no setup, no confirmation.
        
        Fast but unreliable (may lose data).
        
        Sends data in small packets (datagrams).
        
        Lightweight (no extra overhead like TCP).
        
        Used in real-time apps: games, video calls, live streams.
        
        Uses port numbers for sender/receiver.
        
        Only checksum (basic error check).
        
        Best when speed > accuracy.
        
        Example â†’ WhatsApp call, PUBG game.

âœ… Relation / Shortcut

STP = City traffic police system â†’ prevent loops & jams inside LAN (Switches).

UDP = Postcard â†’ fast, simple, but no guarantee (Transport layer).
